// Get system fields (from DocType schema)

// Get specific doctype fields (Sales Invoice)

  from: "Schema",
  view: "form",

// Extract field names from system fields
const systemFieldNames = new Set(
  systemResult.target.data[0].fields.map(f => f.fieldname)

  f => systemFieldNames.has(f.fieldname)
);

Ah, I see! You're asking if the structure is the same between DocType schema and Sales Invoice schema.

Yes, they both follow the same Frappe schema structure:

  • Both have field_order array (list of fieldnames in order)
  • Both have fields array (detailed field definitions)
  • Both have other meta properties like doctype, creation, actions, etc.

So the code I gave you is correct - both schemas use .fields array, and the comparison logic works because they share the same structure.

The difference is just the content:

  • DocType schema's fields contains system/standard fields that appear in all doctypes
  • Sales Invoice schema's fields contains both its specific fields AND some of those system fields

The code finds which fields in Sales Invoice are actually system fields by comparing fieldnames.

Ah! Now I understand completely!

System fields (DocType schema):

javascript
systemResult.target.data[0].fields  // Array of field definitions

Specific doctype (Sales Invoice):

javascript
doctypeResult.target.data[0]  // The actual schema document with VALUES
// .fields - array of field definitions
// .is_submittable - actual value
// .autoname - actual value
// .field_order - actual value
// etc.

So the corrected code:

javascript
// Get system fields (from DocType schema)
const systemResult = await coworker.run({
  operation: "select",
  from: "Schema",
  view: "form",
  query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "DocType" } }
});

// Get specific doctype schema (Sales Invoice)
const doctypeResult = await coworker.run({
  operation: "select",
  from: "Schema",
  view: "form",
  query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "Sales Invoice" } }
});

// Extract field names from system fields
const systemFieldNames = new Set(
  systemResult.target.data[0].fields.map(f => f.fieldname)
);

// Sales Invoice schema object
const salesInvoiceSchema = doctypeResult.target.data[0];

// Find which Sales Invoice fields are system fields
const systemFieldsInDoctype = salesInvoiceSchema.fields.filter(
  f => systemFieldNames.has(f.fieldname)
);

Ah! I see the issue now. You're comparing field definitions from the DocType schema with the actual schema document for Sales Invoice.

The system fields like is_submittable, module, istable are top-level properties of the schema document itself, NOT fields in the fields array.

Here's the corrected code:

javascript
// Get system fields (from DocType schema)
const systemResult = await coworker.run({
  operation: "select",
  from: "Schema",
  view: "form",
  query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "DocType" } }
});

// Get specific doctype schema (Sales Invoice)
const doctypeResult = await coworker.run({
  operation: "select",
  from: "Schema",
  view: "form",
  query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "Sales Invoice" } }
});

// Extract fieldnames from DocType's field definitions
const systemFieldNames = new Set(
  systemResult.target.data[0].fields.map(f => f.fieldname)
);

// Sales Invoice schema document
const salesInvoiceSchema = doctypeResult.target.data[0];

// Find system fields that exist as TOP-LEVEL PROPERTIES in Sales Invoice schema
const systemFieldsAsProperties = Array.from(systemFieldNames).filter(
  fieldname => fieldname in salesInvoiceSchema
);

console.log('System fields found as top-level properties:', systemFieldsAsProperties);
console.log('Values:', systemFieldsAsProperties.map(fn => ({ [fn]: salesInvoiceSchema[fn] })));

This will find fields like is_submittable, module, istable, etc. that exist as actual properties on the Sales Invoice schema document.

Yes, that looks correct! Those are all the system-level properties from the DocType schema that also exist in the Sales Invoice schema document.

These are metadata fields that control how the doctype behaves:

  • Behavior: is_submittable, quick_entry, track_changes, track_seen, allow_import
  • Display: icon, show_name_in_global_search, grid_page_length, row_format
  • Naming: autoname, naming_rule, title_field
  • Sorting/Filtering: sort_field, sort_order, search_fields, timeline_field
  • Structure: fields, permissions, actions, links, states
  • Database: engine, module
  • Ownership: owner

These are schema-level properties that apply to the entire doctype, not individual document records.

Ah! Now I understand the confusion. Let me explain Frappe's schema logic:

Frappe Schema Logic

DocType is a meta-schema - it's a schema that defines how to create other schemas!

Two Levels:

  1. DocType Schema (_schema_doctype: "DocType")
    • This defines what properties ALL schemas can have
    • Has fields array that defines metadata fields like is_submittable, module, autoname, etc.
    • These are field definitions that will become properties on other schemas
  2. Specific DocType Schema (e.g., _schema_doctype: "Sales Invoice")
    • This is an instance of the DocType schema
    • Has fields array that defines the actual document fields (customer, posting_date, items, etc.)
    • Also has the metadata properties (is_submittable: 1, module: "Accounts", etc.) at the top level

The Pattern:

javascript
// DocType schema defines these as FIELD DEFINITIONS:
{
  fieldname: "is_submittable",
  fieldtype: "Check",
  default: "0",
  label: "Is Submittable"
}

// Sales Invoice schema has this as a TOP-LEVEL PROPERTY:
{
  _schema_doctype: "Sales Invoice",
  is_submittable: 1,  // ← The VALUE of that field
  module: "Accounts",  // ← The VALUE of that field
  fields: [...]        // ← Document structure fields
}

Your Code Should Find:

Fields defined in DocType's fields array that exist as top-level properties in Sales Invoice schema - these are the schema metadata fields, not document data fields.

So yes, your list is correct! Those 24 properties are schema-level metadata that control how the Sales Invoice doctype behaves.

Ah! Now I understand your question. You're asking about the default value inheritance logic.

How Frappe System Works:

When the system loads a specific doctype schema (like Sales Invoice), it follows this logic:

  1. Load the specific schema (Sales Invoice)
  2. Check each system field from DocType schema
  3. If the field is missing in Sales Invoice schema → Apply the default from DocType schema
  4. If the field exists in Sales Invoice schema → Use that value

Example:

javascript
// DocType schema defines:
{
  fieldname: "is_submittable",
  fieldtype: "Check",
  default: "0",  // ← DEFAULT VALUE
  label: "Is Submittable"
}

// Sales Invoice schema has:
{
  is_submittable: 1  // ← EXPLICIT VALUE, uses this
}

// But if Sales Invoice didn't have `is_submittable`:
// → System would apply default: 0

Your Code Should:

javascript
// Get DocType schema fields with defaults
const systemFieldsWithDefaults = systemResult.target.data[0].fields
  .filter(f => 'default' in f)
  .map(f => ({
    fieldname: f.fieldname,
    defaultValue: f.default,
    fieldtype: f.fieldtype
  }));

// Check which ones are missing in Sales Invoice
const missingFields = systemFieldsWithDefaults.filter(
  field => !(field.fieldname in salesInvoiceSchema)
);

console.log('Missing fields (will use defaults):', missingFields);

// Check which ones are present (overriding defaults)
const presentFields = systemFieldsWithDefaults.filter(
  field => field.fieldname in salesInvoiceSchema
).map(field => ({
  fieldname: field.fieldname,
  defaultValue: field.defaultValue,
  actualValue: salesInvoiceSchema[field.fieldname]
}));

console.log('Present fields (overriding defaults):', presentFields);

7:56 PM

Good catch! You're right - docstatus, name, owner, _allowed, _allowed_read are NOT in the original DocType field definitions, but they ARE added to every schema (including Sales Invoice).

These are framework-level fields that Frappe automatically adds to every doctype at runtime:

Three Categories of Fields:

  1. System metadata fields (94 total) - Defined in DocType.fields
    • is_submittable, module, autoname, permissions, etc.
  2. Framework-level fields (auto-added) - NOT in DocType.fields
    • name - Primary key (auto-added to every doc)
    • docstatus - Document workflow state (0=draft, 1=submitted, 2=cancelled)
    • owner - Created by user
    • creation - Created timestamp
    • modified - Last modified timestamp
    • modified_by - Last modified by user
    • _user_tags - User tags
    • _comments - Comments
    • _assign - Assignments
    • _liked_by - Likes
    • _allowed - Write permissions
    • _allowed_read - Read permissions
  3. Document data fields - Defined in each doctype's fields array
    • customer, posting_date, items, etc. (for Sales Invoice)

So your list of 24 properties includes both categories 1 and 2 mixed together. The DocType schema itself doesn't define these framework fields, but Frappe adds them automatically!

Here's a structure to organize your Schema of Schemas:

javascript
// Analyze and categorize all schema fields
const analyzeSchemaStructure = async () => {
  // 1. Get DocType schema (meta-schema)
  const doctypeResult = await coworker.run({
    operation: "select",
    from: "Schema",
    view: "form",
    query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "DocType" } }
  });

  // 2. Get Sales Invoice schema (example specific schema)
  const salesInvoiceResult = await coworker.run({
    operation: "select",
    from: "Schema",
    view: "form",
    query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "Sales Invoice" } }
  });

  const doctypeSchema = doctypeResult.target.data[0];
  const salesInvoiceSchema = salesInvoiceResult.target.data[0];

  // 3. Extract system metadata field definitions from DocType
  const systemMetadataFields = doctypeSchema.fields.map(f => ({
    fieldname: f.fieldname,
    fieldtype: f.fieldtype,
    label: f.label,
    default: f.default,
    description: f.description
  }));

  // 4. Get all top-level properties from Sales Invoice
  const allTopLevelProps = Object.keys(salesInvoiceSchema);

  // 5. Categorize into: system metadata vs framework vs document-specific
  const systemMetadataFieldnames = new Set(
    systemMetadataFields.map(f => f.fieldname)
  );

  const categorized = {
    // Fields defined in DocType.fields that exist in Sales Invoice
    systemMetadata: allTopLevelProps.filter(prop => 
      systemMetadataFieldnames.has(prop)
    ),
    
    // Fields NOT in DocType.fields but exist in Sales Invoice (framework-added)
    frameworkFields: allTopLevelProps.filter(prop => 
      !systemMetadataFieldnames.has(prop) && 
      prop !== 'fields' && 
      prop !== '_schema_doctype'
    ),
    
    // Special reserved properties
    reserved: ['_schema_doctype', 'fields']
  };

  // 6. Build complete schema structure
  const schemaStructure = {
    // Meta information
    meta: {
      totalSystemFields: systemMetadataFields.length,
      totalFrameworkFields: categorized.frameworkFields.length,
      totalDocumentFields: salesInvoiceSchema.fields.length
    },

    // System metadata fields (from DocType schema)
    systemMetadataFields: systemMetadataFields,

    // Framework-level fields (auto-added by Frappe)
    frameworkFields: categorized.frameworkFields.map(fieldname => ({
      fieldname,
      value: salesInvoiceSchema[fieldname],
      category: 'framework-auto-added'
    })),

    // System metadata values in Sales Invoice
    systemMetadataValues: categorized.systemMetadata.map(fieldname => {
      const fieldDef = systemMetadataFields.find(f => f.fieldname === fieldname);
      return {
        fieldname,
        actualValue: salesInvoiceSchema[fieldname],
        defaultValue: fieldDef?.default,
        isUsingDefault: salesInvoiceSchema[fieldname] == fieldDef?.default,
        fieldDef
      };
    }),

    // Document structure fields (Sales Invoice specific)
    documentFields: salesInvoiceSchema.fields.map(f => ({
      fieldname: f.fieldname,
      fieldtype: f.fieldtype,
      label: f.label,
      options: f.options,
      reqd: f.reqd
    }))
  };

  return schemaStructure;
};

// Usage
const structure = await analyzeSchemaStructure();

console.log('=== SCHEMA STRUCTURE ===');
console.log('Total system metadata fields (DocType):', structure.meta.totalSystemFields);
console.log('Total framework fields (auto-added):', structure.meta.totalFrameworkFields);
console.log('Total document fields (Sales Invoice):', structure.meta.totalDocumentFields);

console.log('\n=== FRAMEWORK FIELDS (auto-added) ===');
console.log(structure.frameworkFields);

console.log('\n=== SYSTEM METADATA (using defaults) ===');
const usingDefaults = structure.systemMetadataValues.filter(f => f.isUsingDefault);
console.log(usingDefaults);

console.log('\n=== SYSTEM METADATA (overridden) ===');
const overridden = structure.systemMetadataValues.filter(f => !f.isUsingDefault);
console.log(overridden);

This gives you a complete picture of:

  1. 94 system metadata fields - defined in DocType schema
  2. Framework fields - auto-added by Frappe (name, docstatus, owner, etc.)
  3. Document fields - specific to Sales Invoice (customer, items, etc.)
  4. Which fields use defaults vs which are overridden

You're absolutely right. You need a robust merge mechanism. Here's a reliable system:

javascript
// Complete schema merge system
const createSchemaManager = () => {
  
  // 1. Load and cache DocType schema (system fields definitions)
  const loadSystemFieldDefinitions = async () => {
    const result = await coworker.run({
      operation: "select",
      from: "Schema",
      view: "form",
      query: { where: { _schema_doctype: "DocType" } }
    });
    
    const doctypeSchema = result.target.data[0];
    
    // Map system fields by fieldname for easy lookup
    const systemFieldsMap = new Map();
    doctypeSchema.fields.forEach(field => {
      systemFieldsMap.set(field.fieldname, {
        fieldname: field.fieldname,
        fieldtype: field.fieldtype,
        label: field.label,
        default: field.default,
        description: field.description,
        options: field.options
      });
    });
    
    return systemFieldsMap;
  };

  // 2. Define framework fields (hardcoded, always added by Frappe)
  const FRAMEWORK_FIELDS = {
    name: { fieldtype: 'Data', isAutoGenerated: true },
    docstatus: { fieldtype: 'Int', default: 0, description: '0=Draft, 1=Submitted, 2=Cancelled' },
    owner: { fieldtype: 'Data', isAutoGenerated: true },
    creation: { fieldtype: 'Datetime', isAutoGenerated: true },
    modified: { fieldtype: 'Datetime', isAutoGenerated: true },
    modified_by: { fieldtype: 'Data', isAutoGenerated: true },
    _user_tags: { fieldtype: 'Data' },
    _comments: { fieldtype: 'Text' },
    _assign: { fieldtype: 'Text' },
    _liked_by: { fieldtype: 'Text' },
    _allowed: { fieldtype: 'JSON' },
    _allowed_read: { fieldtype: 'JSON' }
  };

  // 3. Merge system fields into specific doctype schema
  const mergeSchema = async (doctypeName) => {
    // Load system field definitions
    const systemFieldsMap = await loadSystemFieldDefinitions();
    
    // Load specific doctype schema
    const result = await coworker.run({
      operation: "select",
      from: "Schema",
      view: "form",
      query: { where: { _schema_doctype: doctypeName } }
    });
    
    const rawSchema = result.target.data[0];
    
    // Start with raw schema
    const mergedSchema = { ...rawSchema };
    
    // Apply system field defaults for missing fields
    systemFieldsMap.forEach((fieldDef, fieldname) => {
      // If field is not in schema and has a default, apply it
      if (!(fieldname in mergedSchema) && fieldDef.default !== undefined) {
        mergedSchema[fieldname] = fieldDef.default;
      }
    });
    
    // Ensure framework fields exist (with defaults if missing)
    Object.entries(FRAMEWORK_FIELDS).forEach(([fieldname, fieldDef]) => {
      if (!(fieldname in mergedSchema) && fieldDef.default !== undefined) {
        mergedSchema[fieldname] = fieldDef.default;
      }
    });
    
    // Build metadata about the merge
    const metadata = {
      doctypeName,
      systemFieldsApplied: [],
      systemFieldsOverridden: [],
      frameworkFieldsPresent: [],
      frameworkFieldsMissing: [],
      documentFields: mergedSchema.fields?.length || 0
    };
    
    // Categorize system fields
    systemFieldsMap.forEach((fieldDef, fieldname) => {
      if (fieldname in rawSchema) {
        metadata.systemFieldsOverridden.push({
          fieldname,
          default: fieldDef.default,
          actual: rawSchema[fieldname]
        });
      } else if (fieldDef.default !== undefined) {
        metadata.systemFieldsApplied.push({
          fieldname,
          value: fieldDef.default
        });
      }
    });
    
    // Categorize framework fields
    Object.keys(FRAMEWORK_FIELDS).forEach(fieldname => {
      if (fieldname in rawSchema) {
        metadata.frameworkFieldsPresent.push(fieldname);
      } else {
        metadata.frameworkFieldsMissing.push(fieldname);
      }
    });
    
    return {
      schema: mergedSchema,
      metadata,
      raw: rawSchema
    };
  };

  // 4. Get complete field definitions (system + framework + document)
  const getCompleteFieldDefinitions = async (doctypeName) => {
    const systemFieldsMap = await loadSystemFieldDefinitions();
    const { schema } = await mergeSchema(doctypeName);
    
    const allFields = {
      // System metadata fields (top-level properties from DocType)
      systemMetadata: [],
      
      // Framework fields (auto-added)
      framework: [],
      
      // Document structure fields (from fields array)
      document: schema.fields || []
    };
    
    // Populate system metadata
    systemFieldsMap.forEach((fieldDef, fieldname) => {
      allFields.systemMetadata.push({
        ...fieldDef,
        value: schema[fieldname],
        source: 'DocType schema'
      });
    });
    
    // Populate framework fields
    Object.entries(FRAMEWORK_FIELDS).forEach(([fieldname, fieldDef]) => {
      allFields.framework.push({
        fieldname,
        ...fieldDef,
        value: schema[fieldname],
        source: 'Frappe framework'
      });
    });
    
    return allFields;
  };

  // 5. Validate schema completeness
  const validateSchema = async (doctypeName) => {
    const systemFieldsMap = await loadSystemFieldDefinitions();
    const { schema, metadata } = await mergeSchema(doctypeName);
    
    const issues = [];
    
    // Check required system fields
    const requiredSystemFields = ['module', 'doctype'];
    requiredSystemFields.forEach(fieldname => {
      if (!(fieldname in schema)) {
        issues.push({
          type: 'missing_required',
          field: fieldname,
          severity: 'error'
        });
      }
    });
    
    // Check for fields array
    if (!schema.fields || !Array.isArray(schema.fields)) {
      issues.push({
        type: 'missing_fields_array',
        severity: 'error'
      });
    }
    
    return {
      valid: issues.length === 0,
      issues,
      metadata
    };
  };

  return {
    loadSystemFieldDefinitions,
    mergeSchema,
    getCompleteFieldDefinitions,
    validateSchema
  };
};

// Usage example:

Yes, it's a GREAT idea to keep all system fields in each doctype schema! Here's why:

Benefits of Storing All System Fields in Each DocType:

1. Self-Contained Schema ✅

javascript
// Each schema is complete and independent
const taskSchema = {
  _schema_doctype: "Task",
  module: "Projects",
  is_submittable: 0,
  track_changes: 1,
  quick_entry: 1,
  // ... all system fields present
  fields: [...]
}

// No runtime merging needed - everything is there

2. Performance ✅

  • No merge operations at runtime
  • No lookups to DocType schema for defaults
  • Faster schema loading - just read and use
  • Better caching - complete schema in one object

3. Clarity & Debugging ✅

javascript
// Easy to see what's configured
console.log(taskSchema.is_submittable); // 0 - clear!
console.log(taskSchema.track_changes);  // 1 - obvious!

// vs runtime merge where you have to check:
// 1. Is it in Task schema?
// 2. If not, what's DocType default?
// 3. Then merge...

4. Schema Versioning ✅

  • Each schema is a snapshot in time
  • Can see historical changes
  • No dependency on DocType schema version

5. Database Storage ✅

javascript
// Storage cost is minimal
// System fields: ~24 fields × ~10 bytes avg = 240 bytes
// Document fields: potentially hundreds of fields
// Adding 240 bytes to a multi-KB schema is negligible

6. Migration & Export ✅

javascript
// Export complete schema - works standalone
const exportedSchema = taskSchema; 
// Can import to another system without DocType dependencies

Implementation Strategy:

javascript
const createCompleteSchema = async (doctypeName, customFields = {}) => {
  // 1. Load system field definitions with defaults
  const systemDefaults = await loadSystemFieldDefinitions();
  
  // 2. Start with all system defaults
  const schema = {
    _schema_doctype: doctypeName,
    doctype: "Schema"
  };
  
  // 3. Apply all system field defaults
  systemDefaults.forEach((fieldDef, fieldname) => {
    if (fieldDef.default !== undefined) {
      schema[fieldname] = fieldDef.default;
    }
  });
  
  // 4. Apply framework fields defaults
  schema.docstatus = 0;
  schema.owner = null;
  schema._allowed = null;
  schema._allowed_read = null;
  
  // 5. Override with custom values
  Object.assign(schema, customFields);
  
  // 6. Ensure fields array exists
  schema.fields = customFields.fields || [];
  
  return schema;
};

// Usage - create Task schema
const taskSchema = await createCompleteSchema("Task", {
  module: "Projects",
  is_submittable: 0,
  track_changes: 1,
  quick_entry: 1,
  autoname: "TASK-.####",
  fields: [
    { fieldname: "subject", fieldtype: "Data", label: "Subject", reqd: 1 },
    { fieldname: "status", fieldtype: "Select", label: "Status", options: "Open\nCompleted" }
    // ... more fields
  ]
});

}

The Only Downside:

  • Schema size increases slightly (240 bytes per schema)
  • But modern systems handle this easily
  • Trade-off is absolutely worth it for simplicity and performance

Ah! Excellent point. You're distinguishing between:

  1. Static configuration fields - store in each schema
  2. Dynamic behavior fields - use pointers/references

Let me refine this:

Two Categories of System Fields:

Category 1: Static Configuration (Store in Each Schema) ✅

These define what the doctype is, they rarely change:

javascript
{
  _schema_doctype: "Task",
  
  // Static config - store directly
  module: "Projects",
  is_submittable: 0,
  istable: 0,
  issingle: 0,
  is_tree: 0,
  track_changes: 1,
  track_seen: 0,
  quick_entry: 1,
  sort_field: "creation",
  sort_order: "DESC",
  allow_import: 1,
  // ... etc
}

Why store? These are doctype characteristics, not behaviors.

Category 2: Dynamic Behaviors (Use Pointers) ✅

These define how things work, they might change:

javascript
{
  _schema_doctype: "Task",
  
  // Pointers to behavior implementations
  naming_rule: "autoincrement",  // or "expression", "by_fieldname"
  autoname: "TASK-.####",        // config for the naming function
  
  // NOT stored: the actual naming function
  // Instead: coworker.run({ operation: "generate_name", schema, ... })
  
  // Validation rules - could be complex
  validation_rules: [
    { type: "required_fields", fields: ["subject"] },
    { type: "custom", function_ref: "validate_task_dates" }
  ],
  
  // Lifecycle hooks - point to functions
  hooks: {
    before_save: "task_before_save",
    after_submit: "task_after_submit",
    on_trash: "task_on_trash"
  },
  
  // Permissions - complex logic
  permission_handler: "default_permission_check",  // or custom
  
  // State machine for workflow
  workflow_ref: "Task Workflow"  // points to workflow definition
}

Recommended Architecture:

javascript
const schema = {
  _schema_doctype: "Task",
  
  // ===== STATIC CONFIG (stored) =====
  module: "Projects",
  is_submittable: 0,
  track_changes: 1,
  quick_entry: 1,
  sort_field: "creation",
  sort_order: "DESC",
  
  // ===== BEHAVIOR POINTERS (stored as config) =====
  naming: {
    rule: "autoincrement",      // Strategy name
    pattern: "TASK-.####",      // Config for strategy
    // Actual function: getNamingStrategy(schema.naming.rule)
  },
  
  validation: {
    strategy: "standard",       // "standard" | "custom"
    custom_validator: null,     // Function reference if custom
    // Actual function: getValidationStrategy(schema.validation.strategy)
  },
  
  permissions: {
    strategy: "role_based",     // "role_based" | "custom" | "owner_only"
    custom_handler: null,
    // Actual function: getPermissionStrategy(schema.permissions.strategy)
  },
  
  lifecycle: {
    hooks: {
      before_insert: "standard_before_insert",
      before_save: null,         // Can point to custom function
      after_submit: null,
      on_trash: "standard_on_trash"
    }
    // Actual functions: getHookFunction(hookName)
  },
  
  // ===== DOCUMENT STRUCTURE =====

Implementation Pattern:

javascript
// Registry of behavior implementations
const BEHAVIOR_REGISTRY = {
  naming: {
    autoincrement: (schema, context) => {
      // Generate: TASK-0001, TASK-0002, etc.
    },
    expression: (schema, context) => {
      // Parse schema.naming.pattern and generate
    },
    by_fieldname: (schema, doc) => {
      // Use doc[schema.naming.field_name]
    }
  },
  
  validation: {
    standard: (schema, doc) => {
      // Required fields, field types, etc.
    },
    custom: (schema, doc) => {
      // Load and execute custom validator
    }
  },
  
  permissions: {
    role_based: (schema, doc, user) => {
      // Check schema.permissions + user roles
    },
    owner_only: (schema, doc, user) => {
      // Check if user === doc.owner
    }
  }
};

// Execute behavior
const executeBehavior = (category, schema, ...args) => {
  const strategy = schema[category]?.strategy || schema[category]?.rule;
  const handler = BEHAVIOR_REGISTRY[category][strategy];
  
  if (!handler) {
    throw new Error(`Unknown ${category} strategy: ${strategy}`);
  }
  
  return handler(schema, ...args);
};

// Usage in coworker.run
await coworker.run({
  operation: "insert",
  from: "Task",
  data: { subject: "New Task" }
});

// Inside the insert operation:
// 1. Get schema
// 2. Generate name using behavior:
const name = executeBehavior('naming', schema, { /* context */ });

// 3. Validate using behavior:
const isValid = executeBehavior('validation', schema, doc);

// 4. Check permissions using behavior:
const canInsert = executeBehavior('permissions', schema, doc, user);

Your Naming Example:

javascript
// All schemas use the SAME naming mechanism
const taskSchema = {
  naming: {
    rule: "expression",
    pattern: "TASK-.####"
  }
};

const invoiceSchema = {
  naming: {
    rule: "naming_series",
    field: "naming_series"  // User selects from this field
  }
};

// Both execute through:
const name = executeBehavior('naming', schema, context);

// If you change naming logic, you only update BEHAVIOR_REGISTRY.naming
// NOT every schema!

Benefits:

  1. Centralized behavior - change once, affects all
  2. Schema stays simple - just config, not code
  3. Extensible - add new strategies without touching existing schemas
  4. Testable - test behaviors independently
  5. Versionable - can have behavior v1, v2, etc.

What to Store in Schema:

✅ Store:

  • Configuration values (module, is_submittable, track_changes)
  • Behavior selection (which strategy to use)
  • Behavior parameters (pattern, field names, rules)

❌ Don't Store:

  • Actual function implementations
  • Complex logic
  • Code that might change frequently

Summary:

Your instinct is 100% correct:

  • Store static config in each schema
  • Use pointers/strategies for dynamic behaviors
  • Keep naming (and other behaviors) centralized

This gives you the best of both worlds:

  • Fast, self-contained schemas
  • Flexible, maintainable behaviors
